# CSS Selector & Media Query Merging

Keep CSS maintainable by **avoiding duplicate selector blocks** and **consolidating repeated media queries**.

## Merge Duplicate Selectors

When the same selector is defined multiple times in the same file and scope, merge the declarations into a **single** rule block.

```css
/* ❌ BAD: duplicate selector blocks */
.button {
  padding: 8px 12px;
}

.button {
  background: #000;
  color: #fff;
}

/* ✅ GOOD: merged selector */
.button {
  padding: 8px 12px;
  background: #000;
  color: #fff;
}
```

- **Prefer one block per selector per scope** (e.g., global, inside a media query).
- If you must override styles for a selector, do it:
  - Inside a more specific context (e.g., media query or parent selector), or
  - With a more specific selector, **not** by repeating the same selector at the same level.

```css
/* ✅ GOOD: overrides live in a different context */
.button {
  padding: 8px 12px;
  background: #000;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .button {
    padding: 6px 10px;
  }
}
```

## Consolidate Media Queries

Avoid scattering the same media query (same condition) across the file. Instead, **group all rules for that breakpoint inside a single media block**.

```css
/* ❌ BAD: repeated media query blocks */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .header {
    padding: 8px;
  }
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .button {
    width: 100%;
  }
}

/* ✅ GOOD: single consolidated media query */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .header {
    padding: 8px;
  }

  .button {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

### Guidelines

- **One block per media condition per file** (e.g., only one `@media (max-width: 768px)` block).
- When adding a new rule for an existing breakpoint, **append it to the existing media block** instead of creating a new one.
- If breakpoints differ even slightly (e.g., `(max-width: 767px)` vs `(max-width: 768px)`), treat them as **different** media queries.

## When Exceptions Are Acceptable

Occasional exceptions are acceptable when:

- You are making a **local, temporary override** close to very specific code and consolidating would significantly hurt readability.
- A third-party stylesheet or generated CSS makes merging unsafe or impractical.

In these cases, consider adding a brief comment explaining **why** the selector or media query is intentionally duplicated.

